<subSubSection pageId="90" pageNumber="90" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="90.[108,637,367,1473]" pageId="90" pageNumber="90">
DISCUSSION: Previous to our research the species of 
<taxonomicName box="[182,286,401,425]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Xiphoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="90" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[182,286,401,425]" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="90">Xiphoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were restricted to 
<collectingCountry box="[486,633,401,425]" name="New Zealand" pageId="90" pageNumber="90">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
. Character documentation for the following two new species augments the generic diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName box="[108,213,503,527]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Xiphoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="90" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[108,213,503,527]" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="90">Xiphoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and expands the known distribution. Both new species have morphology that allows them to be placed in 
<taxonomicName box="[358,463,570,594]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Xiphoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="90" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[358,463,570,594]" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="90">Xiphoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, including: the ovoid body with male slightly more elongate than female; pale tibial spines; vestiture of mixed white scalelike and black simple setae; coiled endosoma with two narrow confluent straps; very large vestibulum strongly extending to right side of bursa copulatrix; posterior wall without extensive structure, but microspicules present on posterolateral margin. On the other hand, their morphology varies modestly from the 
<collectingCountry name="New Zealand" pageId="90" pageNumber="90">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
species and therefore alters the diagnosis of the genus as prepared by 
<bibRefCitation author="Eyles, A. C. &amp; R. T. Schuh" box="[378,633,942,966]" pageId="90" pageNumber="90" pagination="263 - 325" refId="ref68055" refString="Eyles, A. C., and R. T. Schuh. 2003. Revision of New Zealand Bryocorinae and Phylinae (Insecta: Hemiptera: Miridae). New Zealand Journal of Zoology 30: 263 - 325." type="journal article" year="2003">
Eyles and 
<taxonomicName authority="Schwartz &amp; Weirauch &amp; Schuh, 2018" authorityName="Schwartz &amp; Weirauch &amp; Schuh" authorityYear="2018" box="[486,553,942,966]" genus="Schuh" pageId="90" pageNumber="68" rank="genus" status="new genus">Schuh</taxonomicName>
(2003)
</bibRefCitation>
. Notably, the apical portion of the right paramere is moderately long, but the posterior surface lacks serration; the phallotheca is elongate and narrow, but the anterior surface lacks a narrow spine; and the endosoma lacks spines on the dorsal strap basad of secondary gonopore. Likewise, neither species runs to completion in the key of 
<bibRefCitation author="Eyles, A. C. &amp; R. T. Schuh" box="[108,369,1212,1236]" pageId="90" pageNumber="90" pagination="263 - 325" refId="ref68055" refString="Eyles, A. C., and R. T. Schuh. 2003. Revision of New Zealand Bryocorinae and Phylinae (Insecta: Hemiptera: Miridae). New Zealand Journal of Zoology 30: 263 - 325." type="journal article" year="2003">
Eyles and 
<taxonomicName authority="Schwartz &amp; Weirauch &amp; Schuh, 2018" authorityName="Schwartz &amp; Weirauch &amp; Schuh" authorityYear="2018" box="[220,288,1212,1236]" genus="Schuh" pageId="90" pageNumber="68" rank="genus" status="new genus">Schuh</taxonomicName>
(2003)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="90.[108,637,367,1473]" pageId="90" pageNumber="90">
The recognition of 
<taxonomicName box="[356,459,1246,1270]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Xiphoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="90" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[356,459,1246,1270]" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="90">Xiphoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[532,632,1246,1270]" name="Australia" pageId="90" pageNumber="90">Australia</collectingCountry>
, more particularly 
<collectingRegion box="[306,409,1279,1303]" country="Australia" name="Tasmania" pageId="90" pageNumber="90">Tasmania</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[467,636,1279,1303]" country="Australia" name="South Australia" pageId="90" pageNumber="90">South Australia</collectingRegion>
(table 4), fills a geographic gap that bolsters the argument for transantarctic connections in the 
<taxonomicName box="[108,200,1381,1405]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="90" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Phylinae">Phylinae</taxonomicName>
as made by 
<bibRefCitation author="Weirauch, C. &amp; R. T. Schuh" box="[332,632,1381,1405]" pageId="90" pageNumber="90" pagination="473 - 508" refId="ref69201" refString="Weirauch, C., and R. T. Schuh. 2011 (&quot; 2010 &quot;). Southern hemisphere distributional patterns in plants bugs (Hemiptera: Miridae: Phylinae): Xiphoidellus, gen. nov. from Australia and Ampimpacoris, gen. nov. from Argentina, show transantarctic relationships. Invertebrate Systematics 24: 473 - 508." type="journal article" year="2011">
Weirauch and 
<taxonomicName authority="Schwartz &amp; Weirauch &amp; Schuh, 2018" authorityName="Schwartz &amp; Weirauch &amp; Schuh" authorityYear="2018" box="[487,554,1381,1405]" genus="Schuh" pageId="90" pageNumber="68" rank="genus" status="new genus">Schuh</taxonomicName>
(2011)
</bibRefCitation>
, in this case completing the connection between 
<collectingCountry box="[108,248,1448,1472]" name="New Zealand" pageId="90" pageNumber="90">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[298,393,1448,1472]" name="Australia" pageId="90" pageNumber="90">Australia</collectingCountry>
in the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[530,630,1448,1472]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Xiphoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="90" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[530,630,1448,1472]" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="90">Xiphoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
